<subSubSection id="48D355CA8FCDFE4348F75694FB80FDE7" pageId="387" pageNumber="388" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="007606418FCDFE4348F75694FB80FDE7" blockId="387.[151,1436,151,535]" pageId="387" pageNumber="388">
<emphasis id="32BDDA538FCDFE4348F75694FE9EFE20" bold="true" box="[199,315,440,464]" pageId="387" pageNumber="388">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="C7C97DC28FCDFE4349785694FDE6FE20" authorityName="Terayama &amp; Ohbayashi" authorityYear="2003" box="[328,579,440,464]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Gonatopus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="387" pageNumber="388" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hagoromo">
<emphasis id="32BDDA538FCDFE4349785694FDE6FE20" box="[328,579,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="387" pageNumber="388">Gonatopus hagoromo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by 
<bibRefCitation id="64587BB08FCDFE434B1E5694FB38FE3F" author="Terayama &amp; Ohbayashi" box="[814,1181,439,464]" firstAuthor="Terayama" pageId="387" pageNumber="388" pagination="237 - 239" refId="ref370461" refString="Terayama, M. &amp; Ohbayashi, T. (2003) Description of a new species of dryinid wasp (Hymenoptera, Dryinidae) from the Ogasawara Islands, Japan. Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 9 (2), 237 - 239." type="journal article" year="2003">Terayama &amp; Ohbayashi (2003)</bibRefCitation>
from the Ogasawara Islands, known also as Bonin Islands. This archipelago is part of 
<collectingCountry id="78DE46D18FCDFE434B4456F0FC13FE03" box="[884,950,476,499]" name="Japan" pageId="387" pageNumber="388">Japan</collectingCountry>
, but with a subtropical climate. Ogasawara Islands belong to the Oriental zoogeographical region (
<bibRefCitation id="64587BB08FCDFE434ACF56D3FBBDFDE7" author="Inoue &amp; Miyatake" box="[767,1048,511,535]" firstAuthor="Inoue" pageId="387" pageNumber="388" pagination="459 - 475" refId="ref360813" refString="Inoue, H. &amp; Miyatake, Y. (2001) Taxonomic study of the superfamily Psylloidea (Homoptera: Sternorrhyncha) on the Ogasawara (Bonin) Islands. Part 1, Aphalaridae, Psyllidae and Carsidaridae, with descriptions of four new species. Entomological Science, 4, 459 - 475." type="journal article" year="2001">Inoue &amp; Miyatake, 2001</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
